---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '@/components/ui/PageHeader.astro';
import Formula from '@/components/ui/Formula.astro';
import Callout from '@/components/ui/Callout.astro';
import DocRef from '@/components/ui/DocRef.astro';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="TESLA: trust through delay"
  description="How delayed key disclosure lets a public broadcast be authenticated with cheap symmetric MACs."
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="1 · Cryptographic foundations"
    title="TESLA: trust through delay"
    lead="The elegant trick at the heart of OSNMA: keep the key secret while it matters, then reveal it once it is too late to cheat."
  />

  <h2>The dilemma</h2>
  <p>
    Symmetric MACs are cheap, short and perfect for a low-rate broadcast — but they
    need a shared secret, and sharing that secret with every receiver would let any
    of them forge messages. Digital signatures avoid the shared secret but are too
    heavy to attach to every data block. <strong>TESLA</strong> (Timed Efficient
    Stream Loss-tolerant Authentication) resolves the conflict.
  </p>

  <h2>The key idea</h2>
  <p>
    The sender computes a MAC over each message with a key it keeps
    <em>secret for now</em>, and broadcasts the tag immediately. A short time later
    it <em>discloses that key</em>. A receiver therefore:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>buffers the message and its tag when they arrive;</li>
    <li>waits for the key to be disclosed in a later message;</li>
    <li>checks the key belongs to the one-way chain (hash it back toward the trusted root);</li>
    <li>recomputes the MAC over the buffered data and compares.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The security comes entirely from timing. When the tag was transmitted, the key
    was still secret, so no attacker could have produced a valid tag for forged
    data. By the time the key is public, the genuine data is already in the
    receiver's buffer.
  </p>

  <Callout type="security" title="The one condition that makes it work">
    <p>
      The receiver must be sure a key was <em>not already public</em> when it
      received the corresponding tag. That requires loose time synchronisation: the
      receiver has to know roughly what time it is, so it can reject any key that
      arrives suspiciously early.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <div class="level-engineer">
    <h3>The numbers</h3>
    <p>
      OSNMA sets the time-synchronisation requirement to
      <Formula tex="T_L = 30\,\text{s}" /> (one subframe). For normal tags the
      receiver's clock uncertainty must be under 15 s; looser sync (up to 165 s)
      still allows the slow MACs only <DocRef doc="rxg" section="2.1" />. The full
      treatment — the inequalities, the GST sub-frame computation and the anti-replay
      logic — is on the
      <a href="/receiver/time-sync">time synchronisation gate</a> page.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Why it fits Galileo</h2>
  <p>
    OSNMA uses a <strong>single TESLA chain shared by all satellites</strong>. Every
    satellite broadcasting OSNMA discloses the same key at the same epoch, which lets
    one satellite's tags authenticate another satellite's data —
    <em>cross-authentication</em> — and lets a receiver collect authentication faster
    by listening to several satellites at once. A fresh key is disclosed every 30-second
    subframe, carried in the MACK alongside the tags.
  </p>

  <p>
    The chain itself — how keys are generated, disclosed in reverse, and verified
    back to the root — comes alive in the interactive
    <a href="/machinery/tesla-chain">TESLA key chain</a>. To see what anchors the
    root key, read about the <a href="/structures/dsm-kroot">DSM-KROOT</a> and the
    full <a href="/machinery/chain-of-trust">chain of trust</a>.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
